{\plain \fs24 \b PARAMETER SPACE PARTITIONING (OR BEYOND GOODNESS OF FIT)}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 The experimental method of scientific inquiry has proven to work quite well in psychology, \softline
perhaps too well. Its unique blend of methodological control and statistical inference are effective \softline
for testing qualitative (i.e., ordinal) predictions derived from theories of behavior. Data collection \softline
and dissemination have become very efficient, so much so that far more may be known about \softline
behavioral phenomena than is reflected in theory.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 That our knowledge extends beyond the reach of the theory may be a sign of productive science, \softline
and underscores the fact that theories are broad conceptualizations about behavior that cannot be \softline
expected to explain the minutia in data. Cognitive modeling is a research tool that can act as a \softline
counter-force to slow or eliminate this explanatory gap. It compensates for a theory{\u8217\'92}s limitations \softline
of precision in data synthesis, description, and prediction. Whether the model is an \softline
implementation of an existing theory, or a neurally inspired environment is created in which to \softline
study processing (e.g., information integration, representational specificity, probabilistic \softline
learning), models are rich sources of ideas and information on how to think about perception and \softline
cognition. The pros and cons of various implementations can be evaluated. Inconsistencies and \softline
hidden assumptions can come to light during model creation and evaluation. In short, the \softline
modeler is forced to confront the complexity of what is being modeled, and in the process, can \softline
gain insight into the relationship between variables and the functionality of the model (see \softline
Shiffrin & Nobel, 1998 for a personal account of this process).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 Of course, the virtues of modeling are accompanied by vices. One of the more serious, frequently \softline
leveled against connectionist models (Dawson & Shamanski, 1994; McCloskey, 1991), is that \softline
model behavior can be mysterious and difficult if not impossible to understand, which defeats the \softline
purpose of modeling. A model should not be as (or more) complex than the data being described. \softline
Rather, models should offer a simpler description, one that essentially compresses experimental \softline
data.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 The preceding observations are not so much a comment about models or modeling per se, but a \softline
comment about the need for methods for analyzing model behavior. The computational power \softline
and precision of cognitive models requires correspondingly sophisticated tools to study them. \softline
The dearth of such tools may diminish the contribution of modeling to psychology and can also \softline
be an impediment to productive model development. The wide variety of models in the discipline \softline
makes the need for universal tools more pressing and all the more challenging. In this paper, we \softline
introduce a general-purpose model analysis and comparison method in the context of \softline
connectionist models (distributed and localist). Before describing it, current methods are \softline
reviewed.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
