}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 In sum, PSP is a tool for studying the behavior of computational models. It goes beyond \softline
traditional approaches such as goodness-of-fit by focusing on the global behavior of the model in \softline
an entire experimental setting, not just its local behavior in the region occuppied by empirical \softline
data. In doing so, PSP analyses generate a wealth of information about model behavior (e.g., \softline
number, types, and typicality of data patterns). The examples presented here demonstrate the \softline
methods potential as well as the global approach to model analysis. Our hope is that PSP \softline
becomes a standard tool in the modeler{\u8217\'92}s workbench.}}